{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_lunar_ver01/data/sn90050268/00513688866/1921011101/0717.xml":{"full_text":"ITS TIME THE BUYI NG STRIKE IS OVER\nWhat\u2019s the matter with the buying\npublic today. It is the plainest, simplest\nsolution in the world. Even the most cas\nual observer could tell you in a minute\nwhy people stopped short of buying\na few months ago. To begin with\nbig business got scared and the peo\nple found it out and naturally, they\nquit buying, thinking that things\n1 would come down in a jump. Prices\ndid not go up all at once, neither will they\ncome down in a crash. Many people have\nbeen putting off buying the things that\nthey actually need with the thought par\namount in their minds that the bottom\nwould be reached shortly and then they\nwould supply their needs. These same\npeople who have had this thought no\ndoubt were dependent more or less on the\nconstant revolution of business activities\nto maintain them and their jobs. When\npeople stop buying and trading and do\ning business it create^t a depression and\nwhen business depression is felt men\nloose jobs and can\u2019t buy what they need.\nEvery business is more or less de\npendent on the other the same as one\nman\u2019s success is largely responsible for\nsome other man\u2019s success.\nThis condition is practically passed\nnow and people are looking out into the\nfuture with a more hopeful eye as to the\nreal conditions in America today.\nThere is at present a greater abund\nance of crops in the world than there has\nbeen for years. By the great strain that\nhas just passed the American banking in\nstitutions have proven that they are\nas strong as the rock of Gibraltar. The\ntransportation system of the country has\nbeen greatly relieved and commerce can\nbe carried on better now than ever since\nthe war and the railroads are in a letter\nfinancial condition than they have ever\nbeen. Despite the great wave of spending\nthat has been prevalent in this country\nduring the war and since, there is yet a\ngreat surplus of money today due no\ndoubt to the past five years of inflated\nprosperity.\nBusiness depression is a mere state of\nmind and undoubtedly this state has been\nreached and forgotten. The great major\nity of business men are more optimistic\nnow than they have been for months and\nwhy should those who b ave less appear so\npessimistic now.\nThe time to arise is now and the time\nto busy yourself with your business is\nnow.\nIf we will all work and du and save\nand buy, the country is safe, but on the\nother hand, if we all stop work and brood\nand stop buying and want, it will only be\na short time until we will again be in the\nmidst of a depression that is now grad\nually passing.\nTHE DAILY GUARD\nJared E. Trevathan, Manager.\nPHONE 26.\nj REVISED LIST OF\n1 REPRESENTATIVES\nTO LR. MEETING\nHickory Va icy A. G. Gray. Win-\nBp IT. G raj\n5 Cushman W. H. Denison, T. F.\nsl shell. Thomas Dobson. Erank Gray.\nX Alvis -Janies I*. Montgomery.\n2 B'\u25a0 -la Th :nas H< a-. I. H.\nla dl, V. H. Cate\nBatesville M. M. Rutherford. 1. X.\n2 Barnett. Y. Cook. Albert Sinis, D.\nBl D 1: I M Kt 1 M\nglFemll, .1. F. R \u2022M-brough. W. A.\n3 Rutherford J no. X II Inkle, F. P. Al-\nIjbught. .1. B. Johnston. W. B. Head\nx stream, Lawrence Ruddell, X. F. Har-\n8\n\n2\nI Mo..re.\n2 \u00bbr<l W. O. Osborne, I. C. Nuck-\n2 oils; Thos. Wi s .n.\nB| Dota\u2014<\nI\n3 Oil Trough- Sam Brownlow. Erwin\nPelly. L. I Ellis, n, Joe Outlaw, W. A.\nS May hue.\n2 P.,a- nt Plains\u2014Henry Johnson.\nW D. r graM\ni .3 w L. Pa e. W. S. Cul-\nE a I\u2019. De ha, Joe Harmon,\nI\ni. w.I\nNewark E. A. Allen. Chas. Ed-\nE v ards. J. W. Sisk, l\u00bb. C. lu\u00bbne. Vaugh\nVaug an.\n=mr v\nE Grisham.\n\nCaldwell. Wm. Duvall.\n2 M\nE W. McClendon.\n\n5' The state wide meeting ailed for,\nE\ng to be held January lb-1,1. by proclam-\nX'airm of the Governor is held under\nS the auspices of *he Agriculture Com\n\nS iation. Mr. E. J. Rodman, chairman\n3 that nittet as tame